Looks like Etherscan has a tool with a simple "Revoke" button so you don't have to interact directly with the contract.  Go here to check approvals on all your collections!  https://t.co/iJekLKsdDG

@MintyFreshNFT Yes, thanks for the link! I've only seen these tools for ERC-20 not ERC-721 before. It works if you go to the ERC-721 tab and click the "By Contract" toggle. Glad to know I don't have to leave my tool up forever, but the research continues...

This is my first pass at addressing this problem, so I‚Äôm open to any and all feedback or questions you might have. I‚Äôll be doing some research into stolen apes to see if any of them had suspect contract approvals prior to the incident. Will let you know what I find out! 8/

If you check your approvals and find something you don't want, feel free to go direct to the BAYC contract and setApprovalForAll on that address, with the approved value of 0. This will revoke their access to your apes.
https://t.co/GCzI9X0fNV 7/
It absolutely blows my mind that a ‚Äúcheck all approvals‚Äù method is not included in the ERC-721 standard. IMHO that is a gross oversight and something we need to correct in future iterations. 6/
Here's an example of another holder who has approved all for OpenSea, BatchSwap, and the NFT20 liquidity pool. 5/ https://t.co/htnWFcEKU1
Here is an example of one BAYC holder. They have approved OpenSea to operate on all of their BAYC tokens, and they have approved BatchSwap to operate on one of them. 4/ https://t.co/yZfo767s5x

But, for certain collections that use the Open Zeppelin 721 contract, we can listen for events that are fired whenever you set approvals. I set up a @graphprotocol subgraph to scan events on the BAYC contract and provide an approval checker just for this collection. 3/ https://t.co/mmX8oSUFJq

Since approvals are done per-collection, it‚Äôs very hard to see who is approved to operate on your tokens. You‚Äôd basically have to check every single contract address against isApprovedForAll, which is prohibitively expensive/annoying. 2/

The ERC-721 standard includes two crucial methods: approve and setApprovalForAll. Both of these methods will authorize another address to transfer your tokens. Approve sets the approval for a single token id, approvalForAll sets it for all tokens in your wallet. 1/
I wrote a little tool to help you check your contract approvals as a BAYC holder. Check it out at https://t.co/vNoFxRWS2c. Learn more about contract approvals in this thread. üßµ
